I think it is especially enlightening and insightful to learn about Clair Patterson's struggle against industry and their paid scientists, given the current political climate. I was really able to connect to what Peterson was fighting against, lobbying against big oil corporations and their scientists in order to establish the scientific truth. This made me think of climate change today, and how oil companies often paid scientists to manipulate data in order for it to portray something that would be in their interest, e.g. climate change is not real, climate change has been going on even before humans, etc. The similarities between Peterson's world and our world today are frighteningly similar. It look Peterson a long time to establish the negative effects of lead on human health, but how long will it take us to acknowledge the validity of climate change and take action to mitigate its impacts. I also took away an important lesson that I think holds true not just in the field of science, but rather in all aspects of life: data is concrete, but it's interpretations are not. No one will argue that a calculation leads to 24, but what that 24 means is up for debate. 
