Response to
Episode 10 - "The Electric Boy"
@-------------------------------------------------
< YOUR COMMENTS, TAKE-AWAYS, INSIGHTS, QUESTIONS, ETC. HERE >
I really like the way the Cosmos series shows the human side of big discoveries/ advances in science. It's easy to forget that behind each big concept in our textbook there are scientists who toiled to unlock nature's secrets. And that these scientists were/ are people subject to the same sufferings, desires, and faults as all other humans. Born into poverty with little formal education, it's really a lucky coincidence that Faraday was given a chance to develop his talents as a scientist. I found it fascinating that Faraday continued to work and discover despite his memory loss (and resulting depression). Who knows where humanity would be today if it weren't for Faraday's discovery of the deep interconnection between light, magnetism, and electricity.
	  This episode solidified my answer to a question that would usually stump me: "If you were to go back to any point in time, where would you go?". I would go back in time (after transforming into a wealthy, white man) to listen to Faraday give his first Christmas lecture in London's Royal Institution. I would then attempt to loiter in his laboratory, a place so crucial to the future course of human existence. 



